<TITLE>Reinvention Express 10/15/96</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="/gifs/nprlogo2.gif">
<BR>
<BR>
     <H1 ALIGN=LEFT><I>REINVENTION EXPRESS</I></H1>
<TABLE width="60%">
<TR><TD><basefont size=7>Calendar</basefont></TD><TD align=right valign=bottom>October 15, 1996</TD></TR> 
</TABLE>
<BR CLEAR=left>
<HR>
  <CENTER>
	An Information Sheet for Federal Communicators, Managers, Workers, and Their Partners--Pass It On <P>
</CENTER>
Free Satellite Downlink
<H2>December 5-6: Conference on Leading Change in the 21st Century</H2>
	Change is a way of life in government these days. How can we take charge of change, rather than just reacting to it? This national conference has some answers. It's an opportunity for federal workers to share experiences and learn practical tools for leading change as we move into the next century.  <A HREF="/library/announc/regfax.html">The Leading Change Conference</A> will be held December 5-6 at the Natcher Center in Bethesda, MD.
<P>
	John P. Kotter, Harvard Business School professor and author of the best-selling book<I> Leading Change,</I> will participate via satellite from Cambridge. Keynote speaker is James Lee Witt, Director of the Federal Emergency Management Agency, who in 3 years led that agency from threat of abolishment by Congress  to winner of the 1996 Public Service Excellence Award. He will participate via satellite from the USDA Satellite Conference Center in Washington, DC.  This conference is sponsored by the National Performance Review, the Consortium for Culture Change, the Federal Quality Consulting Group, and the Human Resource Development Council. 
<P>
<B>Conference Fee Is Unbelievable--Register Now</B><BR>
	You can't beat the conference fee--it's only &#036:45.  It covers all conference materials, including a copy of John Kotter's book. At this price, you'd better act fast. <B>You must register and pay by November 15.</B>  Information on the conference is posted on NPR's web site at http://www.npr.gov. Go to" News Room" and look under "Announcements." If you have questions, contact Dr. Lynn S. Kahn by e-mail: <I>lynn.kahn@npr.gsa.gov</I> or call (202) 632-0232.

<P>
<B>For Satellite Information </B><BR>
	Remote sites are invited to participate in the free live <A HREF="/library/announc/box.html">satellite segment</A> from noon until 4 pm ET on December 5. Or, they may also create parallel conferences with their own guest speakers, break-out sessions, and interaction with the Natcher Center site. Remote sites may purchase conference materials for a small fee if they wish. Federal training or distance learning directors should contact Dr. Alexander Gettesman at e-mail: <I>nmc5amg@bms200.med.navy.mil</I> or (202) 762-3839. Satellite coordinates will not be available until early November.
<P>
	You're also invited to contribute to NPR's online tool box, which will be rolled out at the conference. Check it out on the NPR Web site at http://www.npr.gov. Go to "How to Tools" and click on <A HREF="/library/papers/bkgrd/common.html">"Common Sense Tools."</A>
<P>
<B>October 15-17: 4th Annual Quality Air Force Symposium & Expo </B><BR>
	The 4th Annual Quality Air Force Symposium and Expo '96 will be in Montgomery, AL,  October 15-17.  For program and registration information, contact (800) 204-2005. 
<P>
<B>October 21: Regulators Will Hold Interagency Reinvention Forum</B><BR>
	The Food and Drug Administration will be the host of the next Interagency Regulatory Reinvention Forum on October 21. This interagency cooperative effort was started by FDA,  the Environmental Protection Agency and the Occupational Safety and Health Administration. They found joint meetings to share reinvention ideas  so successful they decided to invite other agencies. If you would like to join this growing group in the Washington, DC area, call FDA's Marie Urban or Audrey Borja at (301) 827-0946.
<P>
<B>October 29: Education and Training Expo: Conference for the 21st Century</B><BR>
	The Department of the Treasury and the General Services Administration are co-hosting an expo on Multimedia Emerging Technologies at the National Museum of Women in the Arts, 1250 New York Avenue, NW, in Washington, DC, from 8:30 am to 3 pm on October 29.  The expo will feature the latest in instructional software design, desktop presentations, network and computer-based training, telecomuting, online degree programs, and more. Vendors will offer presentations and exhibits. The event is free to government employees. To register, call (301) 206-2940.
<P>
<B>November 18-20: Strategic Planning for Government</B><BR>
	The 5th National Conference on Strategic Planning for Government: Complying with the Government Performance and Results Act will be November 18-20 in Washington, DC. It will feature case studies from NASA, the Social Security Administration, Army Armament Research, Development and Engineering Center (1996 President's Quality Award winner), and the Department of Defense. For information, call (800) 420-2145 or visit this Web site: <A HREF="http://www.iqpc.com">http://www.iqpc.com.</A>
<P>
<B>November 18-20: GOAL/QPC'S  Annual Conference</B><BR>
	GOAL/QPC's Annual Conference is November 18-20 in Orlando, FL. The theme is "Lessons from Leaders: Building Adaptive Organizations to Thrive in Turbulent Markets."
Participants will hear presentations on quality success stories from many sectors, including  military, government, education, and health care. For more information, call (800) 643-4316.
<P>
<B>November 19-20: First Annual Fall Benchmarking Conference</B><BR>
	The Interagency Benchmarking and Best Practices Council and the National Performance Review invite federal employees  to a conference November 19-20 in the Howell Auditorium at the Defense Systems Management College at Fort Belvoir, VA. It's free!  Keynote speaker is Elaine Kamarck, Senior Policy Advisor to the Vice President. For information visit the Web site, 
<A HREF="http://www.va.gov/fedsbest/index.htm"> http://www.va.gov/fedsbest/index.htm </A>or call S.G. Fenwick at (202) 586-8974.
<P>
<B>December 9-11: Restructuring Internal Communications in Government Agencies</B><BR>
	Is your agency prepared to meet the challenge of communicating radical change? This Washington, DC, conference includes case studies from the Social Security Administration, Naval Air Warfare Center, Department of Energy,  Minnesota Department of Revenue, and the City of Phoenix.  Speakers will show how to strengthen internal communications on a shoe-string budget, exploit the use of technology, including intranets,  and measure communications effectiveness. Call (800) 420-2145 or visit  
<A HREF="http://www.iqpc.com">http://www.iqpc.com </A>for more information.
<P>
